comments.text: Hidden bug in Particle.pde ln. 84 / 85: Better to dir.mult(mag); then acc.add(dir);
Oops, and consider change Particle.pde ln. 65 to:     this.sizeMult = map(sin(frameCount*0.02), -1, 1, 0.22, 0.75);	this.sizeMult = this.sizeMult * this.sizeMult;

And I don't know whether you guys found that most of the particles goes to left top directions. That's because we add frameCount to first and second parameter of noise(), rather than use is as third dimension/parameter. See my fork with this changed. Although I think this original sketch is much better anyway!.

If we add frameCount to first two parameters, then if the noise let the particle go upper left, then it's deltaX and deltaY cancels the ++frameCount, and it enters a stable state, which might not intended by design?
Escape, thanks for the comments but this sketch is a fork. The majority of the code isn't written by me so I won't be making any changes. Feel free to fork this one and implement them yourself :)

visuals.title: OdeToGameOfLife
visuals.description:
Click to restart. 
Based on John Conway's 1970 algorithm. 
Each box follows 4 simple rules.

1. Any live cell with fewer than two live neighbors dies, as if caused by under-population.

2. Any live cell with two or three live neighbors lives on to the next generation.

3. Any live cell with more than three live neighbors dies, as if by overcrowding.

4. Any dead cell with exactly three live neighbors becomes a live cell, as if by reproduction.

Sometimes all units die, other times some units stabilize.

This is slightly altered from original as found in Chapter 12 of Ira Greenberg's Creative coding. All I've done is exaggerate some of the settings, add some color and set the functions out in multiple tabs. It is interesting how the simulated gravity and elasticity sets up periods of synchronicity as some points fall together and then apart.
